  "topic_id": "T09.01",
  "topic_name": "Cartesian Plane and Distance Formula",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "The Cartesian plane is a two-dimensional coordinate system where any point can be represented by an ordered pair (x, y). The x-coordinate represents horizontal distance from the origin, and the y-coordinate represents vertical distance. The distance formula d = √[(x₂-x₁)² + (y₂-y₁)²] calculates the distance between two points. The section formula for internal division gives the coordinates of a point dividing a line segment in a given ratio. The mid-point formula is (x₁+x₂)/2, (y₁+y₂)/2. Linear equations in two variables can be represented as straight lines on the Cartesian plane, with the slope-intercept form y = mx + c where m is the slope and c is the y-intercept.",
    "rules": [
      "The Cartesian plane has four quadrants with different sign conventions",
      "Distance is always positive or zero",
      "The distance formula is derived from the Pythagorean theorem",
      "Mid-point formula is a special case of section formula with ratio 1:1",
      "Slope m represents the rate of change of y with respect to x",
      "Parallel lines have equal slopes",
      "The y-intercept is the value of y when x = 0"
    ]
  },
